<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>Okay form what i know about this ( alot ) is that charm is capped at some level what this means is that anything above this certain lvl can not be affected by charm.. thats why we get beguile. Begule also cancels out at some level which is 40 i think because i can still use it on Spectres. Also the length that is possible for it to last increases. which means ex. :  charm is a 1/4 chance itll last 2 minutes but beguile is a 4/10 chance it will last 5 minutes.... odds get better as well as the range of levels and length in time.  in conclusion this spell is VERY effective and i recommend it to be used versus Spectres so as u can fight or pull more than one, or any MoB for that matter.</font></td></tr></table>
<BR>
<table width=100%>
<tr>
<td width=50%><font color=white>Posted By: Cylos</font></td><td width=50% align=right><font color=white>2000-08-23 13:08:16</font></td></tr><tr>
<td colspan=2 bgcolor="#0000AF"><font color=white>Charm has a level cap of 25 -  hence we get Beguile at 24.   As far as the duration of Charm/Beguile, there are a number of different factors that go into that, not to mention good old random luck.  The most well known are: 1.) Your Charisma,  2.) The Mobs Magic Resistance,  and  3.) Your level relative to your target.   This last one is the most important, as I have charmed greenies for what seems an eternity, while I have never had a Yellow or red mob last anywhere close to the maximum duration.   I believe you can charm mobs up to 5 lvls above you, although I personally try to stick to blues, as they are more predictable and the charm will actually last thru one (or more) full battle.   If you want maximum duration, buff your charisma up, Tash your target’s MR down, and make sure it cons green. <BR>
<BR>
Personally, I think this is the best spell line Enchanters have, and whoever said Enchanters can’t solo never properly mastered this spell.   After the mid teens when our Animated pets become all but useless, this is the way to go.  I soloed from 17 – 20 in the Beholder’s Maze by charming the minos against one another.  The trick is to charm one, root the rest (so they fight your pet and don’t run after you), and make sure your pet just BARELY wins.   If you play your cards right, you’re pet should be the last one standing with only a sliver of health, so when you invis to break charm, one nuke and it’s dead.   So you get XP for all the mobs your pet kills, and then you get the XP for killing your pet.   At my best, I charmed one yellow mino against two high blues; I nuked or dotted as needed to ensure that the yellow pet won, just barely, then I invised and easily killed the yellow mino with one shot.   What other class can solo two high blues and a yellow at the same time, without getting hit once?   Even in groups, it’s a great way to turn the tides of battle; if you are 4 on 4, Charm can instantly turn that into 3 on 5 in your favor.   The two rules of thumb I go by when charming; one, always always always Tash your intended pet, and two, always root whatever your pet is fighting, so that if charm breaks early, you only have one angry mob to contend with.  Also, while fighting in the Beholder’s Maze, I always traded Breeze for a Sow, and fought by the zone, since pulling is no fun if you can’t out run them and end up getting pounded (and Enchanters aren’t real great in the AC / HP dept).  Generally, I’d pull two or three minos, outrun them for a bit, stop and tash one or two as they caught up (or mez any extra muddies that I’d picked up) and start off again towards the zone.     Now at lvl 23, I can walk into Najena, charm a high blue Tentical Terror, and lay waste to the upper half of the zone (which is all pretty much green to me anyway, but it’s fun mass carnage.)   I have also had luck charming TTs against each other there, although they can still cast on me while rooted, but it’s a low damage spell, and I have a high MR.   The TTs generally spawn in pairs, and little else that will aggro around them (if you’re careful when you root).  Also, they are far enough apart that charming one will not aggro the other right away.<BR>
<BR>
Anyway, didn’t mean to write a book, just to illustrate my point; this is the best tool for Enchanters, hands down.   We don’t get high damage output, not in DD or DoTs, and certainly not in melee, but here is where you can out damage even wizzy and monks, and with a lot less mana and health loss.   Let the mobs fight each other; after all, every point of damage one does to the other is one less you need to inflict AND one less you have to take.   Talk about mana efficiency.  It does take a bit of practice to get a feel for holding a COMMANDABLE pet, and the reaction of the other uncharmed mobs it’s attacking (they’ll come after you if you are too close, which is why you root).   But once you get the knack, this is the best way I know of for Enchanters to inflict damage to mobs, whether soloing or grouped.<BR>
<BR>
So good luck!  Hope this helps someone discover how powerful this spell really is.<BR>
<BR>
Cylos<BR>
23rd Enchanter of Xegony<BR>
</font></td></tr></table>
